I FINALLY DID IT!

After several failed attempts I finally have a happy, thriving atrawberry patch that is producing beautiful, delicious fruit. If at first you don't succeed, try, try again (bc no one has to know how many plants you murked figuring it out 🫣😂)

Keys to Success So Far...

LOCATION. LOCATION. LOCATION: my strawberries get AM sun only

FOOD: I've been spraying with worm tea and they seem to love it. 

PROTECTION: drawstring bags for physical barrier protection & garlic for companion planting aka sends bunnies & ants packing protection play a huge part in getting berries to ripeness unharmed.

Honorable mention goes to MULCH for keeping the roots cool and the ripening berries from touching the soil, which could cause them to rot, SNAPDRAGONS that helped pull in pollinators and my @garden_in_minutes grid for making sure the plants were evenly watered without the crowns getting wet!

It was cold & windy yesterday so I went to check on our Katy Apricot. This tree is on year 2 in the ground. Last year it didn't flower at all and only produced a moderate number of leaves. This year it was covered in flowers before I saw a single leaf and to my surprise, it set a decent amount of fruit, too!

I'm still vaguely shocked by actual fruit growing in my backyard 😅.

I did my 1st worm castings spray with @azwormfarm a few weeks ago and all my trees have really taken off since. My goal is to be on top of feeding/fertilizing this year and their service is a great foundation.

Mangoes in the desert?! 🤯

Tree sourced via @shamus_oleary_
I'm constantly looking for ways to be more efficient with time and water in the garden. I own a few self-watering planters but I've never made one before. Here's part 1 of my first attempt.

Here's part II of my self-watering planter experiment.

Originally, I wanted to put the tallest plants, the pencil cactus (thriller), in the center and put the heather (filler) and crassula (spiller) around it but once I got into the pots I realized the heather would be impossible to separate and when I checked the growth rate, I saw it would likely be the fastest growing thing in the pot so - change of plans!

I actually prefer this design in the sense that it's a little less 'expected'. It's giving southwest forest wedding centerpiece and I'm not even mad. 

Can't wait to see how these look as the crassula starts spilling and the heather fills out a bit more!

Went to pick up my dwarf coconuts and variegated ginger, left with them plus 4 canna lilies, a starfruit, a Pakistani mulberry, and an ice cream banana. 

Whoops. 

(PS: special thx to reels for messing up my captions. 🙃)

We finally put all the succulents we grabbed at the @dbgphx plant sale a few weeks ago to good use!

Our front yard is morning sun, which definitely helps, but even so we needed to find low-water, drought friendly plants that would not only add color & visual interest, but also survive our summers.

We'll continue watering periodically to help these plants get established before the worst of the heat. In the meantime I'm loving how adding these plants created a focal point around our address sign. 

#curbappeal
My design philosophy: when in doubt, add more plants. 🪴

These tomato plants went from barely hanging on to total jungle in just a few weeks.

After watching some @epicgardening vids to get my courage up, I finally tackled the overgrowth with 3 goals in mind:

1) Increase Airflow
2) Remove Suckers
3) Make Fruit Easier to See/Reach

There's definitely more trimming I could do but the plants are manageable for now and no longer smothering their companion plants & there's so much that needs doing this time of year in the garden so I'll circle back later.

A day of digging in the dirt will build up an appetite. I threw together last night's dill & lemon balm sauteed veggies and rice with green olives, roasted cherry tomatoes, red onions, pressed lemon garlic tofu and garlic naan.

From Garden to Table in 30(ish) Seconds!

I've never attempted garlic before but I knew from research that when the lower leaves start to yellow it can mean the bulbs are ready. Mine are showing signs so I did a test pull to check!

Pro Tip: don't pull all the radishes, onions, carrots etc at once if you aren't sure they're ready. Pull 1 or 2 at a time to test before you dig up the whole bunch. It's hard to be patient but ruining the whole harvest by pulling early is no bueno. 

This pasta dish was very satisfying with just the right amount of spice. The garlic smelled SO strong (I love garlic, so not an issue for me, lol) and taste/texture were perfect. I'm going to wait to pull the rest bc I want to attempt storing some (yikes!) and I need to do some research.

I was today years old...

After seasons of crushing, mashing and mangling seedling roots trying to wrestle them out of trays, I've finally found the trick - a landscaping stake!

Position the points of the stake to either side of the transplant and push into the soil about an inch. Squeeze gently and lift.

That's it!

This works best on moist soil, so give your tray a bit of water before you attempt this for best results.

My very first garlic season is officially over!

I'll be experimenting with braiding and curing these cloves. I may even try freeze drying but just curing them for now is enough to get them stable.

These were companion plants for my strawberries. They helped keep bunnies and ants away. I think I'll try replacing them with green onions until it's cool enough in Phoenix to replant garlic again. 

These are a mix of Sicilian & Cali Softneck Garlic. Cloves all came from @sandiegoseedcompany

Focused on the coming abundance.

I didn't know what to expect on a Sisters of Yoga retreat.

I'll admit I arrived a little skeptical and a little guarded but in less than 48 hours it felt like we had all known each other for years and I'm so grateful. I was missing that in my life & didn't even know it yet.

So what does one do on a retreat? 

I can tell you what I did. It was a lot of talking - deep conversations, shallow conversations, long and short conversations. Conversations of every size and shape just as we brought together women from every walk and path of life. It was so amazing to hear myself in their stories and know that they heard themselves in mine.

We ate good - Lord, did we eat! Homemade tortillas and passionfruit ice cream. Fresh squeezed juices, chocolate avocado mousse and ripe, seasonal produce. Each day started and ended for me with herbal tea - moringa, milk thistle and Dong Quai. So many plantbased options that emphasized whole foods and no added sugars. We were nourished from the inside out (sometimes against our will, 😅) but ultimately, we knew everything we were eating was made with love and made with the intention of helping us heal.

We wrote in our journals and shared resources - books and apps, scraps of wisdom and advice. We meditated together, and cried together and laughed together and sang together and howled at the moon together and pushed each other with love - some of it tough but all of it intentional and kind.

We created a safe space in a moment in time that has changed everyone blessed to have been in attendance. I know it changed me.

Thank You. 💜

Drowning in garden zucchini? A fresh, protein-packed salad with summery Mediterranean-inspired flavors is a great way to use some of it up!

I also added a few spices, including maldon sea salt, cumin, garlic powder and tofu 'croutons' 

A spiralizer creates beautiful zucchini ribbons that you can customize with a variety of toppings. Try different flavor profiles to come up with your own favorites. AND, best of all, you'll use approximately half a large zucchini for each serving - helping clear much needed space for tomorrow's harvest.

Zucchini, tomatoes, moringa & green onion all pulled from the garden. 

Ingredients Used:

1 Lg Zucchini
1 Can Chickpeas
Olive Oil Vinaigrette- I used Newman's Own 
1 Lg Lemon 
1/2 Med Red Onion
3-4 Lg Sprigs Basil - I used Sweet & Dark Opal
1-2 Cups Cherry Tomatoes
Moringa Flowers (optional)
1/4 cup Moringa Leaves (optional)
Flake Sea Salt, Lemon Pepper, Cumin & Garlic Powder to taste.

These three watch us eat out of the garden all the time and their general rule of thumb seems to be 'if you're eating, you should share!'

So, we do. 😋

Tomatoes are safe for dogs to enjoy in moderation and my pups KNOW it. All 3 of them stand by while I pick, waiting for their share. 

I can't blame them, though. Sun-ripened, inseason cherry tomatoes are absolutely delicious. 💯 

I'm suddenly realizing I'm probably going to have 40 million volunteers next season 😳 😅.

Worth it.

Zucchini, peppers, peaches, basil & other herbs pulled from the garden. 

I've never tried tofu on the grill before and I was worried about sticking, but we used the 'onion' trick to clean the grate and had 0 sticking issues. 😉

I, luckily, have very mild allergies. But when I woke up this past Saturday and my eyes immediately started weeping I knew I'd be miserable all day if I didn't do something. Luckily, this tea is strong enough to work for both me and my husband (his allergies are much worse) and you don't have to remember to take it everyday for it to work.

My Allergy Tea Recipe

Organic Rooibos Tea (1 tsp/cup)
Roselle Hibiscus 
Turmeric ( I used @myteadrop)
Lemongrass

Optional
Ginger
Lemon balm
Coconut or Date Sugar (to taste)
Sugarcane
Moringa (I added leaves & dried flowers)
Lemon 

Follow your normal tea brewing procedure, then strain & serve. Sweetner is optional but I couldn't pass up the opportunity to use our sugarcane for the first time! I especially love this tea iced. The flavor is so refreshing. Rooibos, Ginger & Turmeric do a lot of the work here to handle inflammation and soothe allergies  but Lemongrass is also very powerful. Ginger or Turmeric alone will work in a pinch but the two together is more effective. The Hibiscus is very cooling, helps flush excess water and smoothes out the flavor. It's also high in Vitamin C. I like to make a big batch a few times a week during allergy season & pack a thermos for B & I to take for work. It's not unusal to find me pouring cups of it for people in the office that forgot their Claritin 😂. 

Lemongrass, Roselle, Moringa and Sugarcane from the garden.

The beauty of a (permaculture) garden. 
This place sustains me in more ways than one.

Kiwano Melon, aka African Horned Cucumber is an unique looking fruit that packs a nutritional punch. They're high in magnesium, zinc and vitamin C, making them great for everything from bone density and eyesight to immune support and skin health.

I thought my attempt this year was a bust but I spotted 6 or 7 of them this morning after clearing out some old squash vines. Hopefully, with the additional sunlight, they'll start ripening.
